"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Deuteronomy chapters 26–27
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-deuteronomy-26-27-fill.py

Key christological decisions for this range:
- Ch 26 firstfruits liturgy: Paul's 1 Cor 15:20,23 ('Christ the firstfruits') is the
  primary NT hermeneutic; the basket-offering is treated as a shadow of the resurrection
  offering of the firstborn from the dead
- The Heilsgeschichte recitation (vv. 5-9) is treated as the prototype confession that
  the NT reshapes as the Gospel narrative: descent into vulnerability, cry to God,
  mighty deliverance; Phil 2:6-8 / 1 Cor 15:3-4 pattern
- v. 12-15 tithe declaration ('I have done everything you commanded') treated as the
  formula Christ alone perfectly fulfills; John 17:4 / John 19:30 connection
- vv. 16-19 mutual covenant declaration: 1 Pet 2:9 applies 'am sĕgullāh to the church;
  Rev 21:3 ('they will be his people') is the eschatological fulfillment of the formula
- Ch 27 stone-inscriptions treated as the law-on-stone vs. law-on-heart contrast
  (2 Cor 3:3; Jer 31:33); the Ebal/Gerizim binary treated as absorbed into Christ who
  takes the Ebal-curse dimension (Gal 3:10-13)
- Deut 27:26 (the closing curse) is Paul's proof-text in Gal 3:10 that all humanity is
  under law's curse before Christ's redemption — the most direct NT link in the chapter
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DEUT = {
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>The firstfruits law opens with 'when you have come into the land' — the conditional frame marks land possession as a gift that generates an obligation to return the first portion to the Giver. Paul's description of the resurrected Christ as 'the firstfruits' (<em>aparchē</em>) of the dead (1 Cor 15:20,23) deliberately invokes this firstfruits theology: just as the firstfruits basket consecrates the whole harvest to YHWH, Christ's resurrection as the firstfruits consecrates and guarantees the full resurrection harvest of all who belong to him. The ritual of ch 26 is a shadow of the resurrection economy.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The first of all the produce (<em>rēʾšît kol-pĕrî hāʾădāmāh</em>) must go to the sanctuary — the first and best belongs to YHWH. In Paul's resurrection theology, Christ as firstfruits is not merely the first chronologically but the first in quality and representativeness: his resurrection is the prototype that determines the character of the whole harvest (1 Cor 15:42-44). The basket brought to 'the place YHWH your God will choose' (i.e., Jerusalem) anticipates the ascension: Christ, the firstfruits offering, is presented in the heavenly sanctuary (Heb 9:24: 'he entered heaven itself, to appear before God on our behalf').</p>",
    "3": "<p>The declaration 'I have come into the land he swore to our ancestors to give us' is a confessional testimony — the worshipper does not merely bring produce but verbally acknowledges the covenant history that makes the harvest possible. Jesus taught his disciples to pray with the same logic: 'your kingdom come, your will be done on earth as in heaven' (Matt 6:10) — the prayer form that acknowledges YHWH's sovereign gift as the precondition for human life. The priest who receives the basket here is a type of Christ the great high priest who receives the offerings of his people (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The priest sets the basket before the altar — an act of presentation and consecration. In the NT typological frame, Christ himself is simultaneously the priest who presents the offering and the offering presented. Hebrews 9:14 describes him as one who 'through the eternal Spirit offered himself unblemished to God' — the priest-and-offering convergence that Deuteronomy's separation of roles (the worshipper brings; the priest presents) could only hint at. The altar before which the basket is set is the place of encounter between the human gift and the divine acceptance.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'My father was a wandering Aramean' (<em>ʾărammî ʾōbēd ʾābî</em>) — the covenant's founding confession begins with radical humility: Israel's ancestor was a displaced foreigner with no established place or power. The Incarnation repeats this pattern: the Son of God 'emptied himself, taking the form of a servant, being born in the likeness of men' (Phil 2:7). Paul reads the descent-into-vulnerability pattern as the christological template (2 Cor 8:9: 'though he was rich, for your sake he became poor'). The few who went down to Egypt becoming a great nation is the resurrection-shape embedded in Israel's founding story: death and smallness become life and abundance.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Egyptian bondage — 'they treated us harshly, oppressed us, and imposed ruthless forced labor' — is the nadir of descent in the narrative. In the christological reading, the Cross is this nadir: Jesus, delivered to the nations, subjected to their cruelty, forced to bear the weight of the world's sin. The trajectory of the Heilsgeschichte recitation (vv. 5-9) — from free ancestor to bondage to divine deliverance — is the same trajectory as the Gospel: from the eternal Son's freedom, through the bondage of incarnation and crucifixion, to the deliverance of resurrection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'We cried to the LORD, the God of our ancestors, and the LORD heard our voice' — the cry to YHWH in extremity answered by divine hearing is the prayer theology of the Psalms (Ps 22:24: 'he has not hidden his face from him but has listened to his cry for help'). Psalm 22 is itself the cry of the crucified one — Jesus quotes its opening from the cross (Matt 27:46; Mark 15:34). The pattern of Deuteronomy 26:7 is enacted in the passion: the cry from dereliction is heard, and the Resurrection is the divine 'hearing' that vindicates the sufferer. Hebrews 5:7 applies the cry-and-hearing pattern directly to Jesus.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The LORD brought us out of Egypt with a mighty hand and an outstretched arm, with great awe-inspiring acts and with signs and wonders' — the standard exodus formula. Stephen's speech in Acts 7:36 applies 'signs and wonders' to Moses's acts as a type of Christ's acts; the author of Hebrews applies 'signs and wonders' to the apostolic proclamation of Christ's salvation (Heb 2:4). Paul describes the Gospel's power using the same vocabulary (Rom 15:19: 'by the power of signs and wonders'). The exodus's 'mighty hand and outstretched arm' becomes the resurrection's 'surpassing greatness of his power' (Eph 1:19-20).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'He brought us to this place and gave us this land, a land flowing with milk and honey' — the earthly inheritance is the temporal type of the eternal inheritance. Hebrews 11:16 explicitly reinterprets the patriarchs' journey: 'they were longing for a better country — a heavenly one.' Peter addresses the diaspora Christians as those who have been 'born again to a living hope ... and into an inheritance that can never perish, spoil, or fade, kept in heaven for you' (1 Pet 1:3-4). The milk-and-honey land is the shadow of the eternal homeland Christ has prepared (John 14:2-3: 'I am going there to prepare a place for you').</p>",
    "10": "<p>'I bring the firstfruits of the soil you have given me' — the worshipper sets down the basket and bows before YHWH. The prostration (<em>hishtaḥăwāh</em>) is the covenant response to gift: the proper posture before the Creator-Giver. Every knee will bow before Christ (Phil 2:10-11), whose worship is not coerced but the fitting response of creation to the one through whom 'all things were created' (Col 1:16). The firstfruits as gift returned to the Giver anticipates the Son's return of the kingdom to the Father: 'then the Son himself will be made subject to him who put everything under him, so that God may be all in all' (1 Cor 15:28).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The rejoicing at the firstfruits festival includes the Levite and the foreigner — the covenant community's joy is explicitly extended to the socially marginal. Christ's table fellowship with sinners, tax collectors, and Gentiles enacts the same inclusive rejoicing: the feast of salvation is not reserved for the ethnically pure. In the eschatological banquet (Rev 19:9: 'blessed are those who are invited to the wedding supper of the Lamb'), every tribe and nation and people rejoices together. The foreigner (<em>gēr</em>) included in Israel's festival joy is a type of the Gentile incorporation that Paul describes as 'heirs together with Israel' (Eph 3:6).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The third-year tithe given to the Levite, the foreigner, the fatherless, and the widow is the covenant redistribution system — surplus directed to the covenant community's most vulnerable. Jesus instructs his disciples to practice the same deliberate redistribution: 'when you give a banquet, invite the poor, the crippled, the lame, the blind' (Luke 14:13). The early church's common life (Acts 2:44-45; 4:32-35) is the NT fulfillment of the tithe-distribution principle: no one in the covenant community was to be left without provision. Christ himself is 'the poor one' who makes others rich (2 Cor 8:9), and his redistribution is the model for the community's.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The tithe declaration begins: 'I have removed from my house the sacred portion and given it to the Levite, the foreigner, the fatherless, and the widow, according to everything you commanded me.' This is the covenant accountability statement — the worshipper reports full compliance with the distribution command. Jesus's parable of the talents (Matt 25:14-30) operates on the same logic: the servants who gave an account of their stewardship to the returning master. In Rev 14:4 the 144,000 are described as 'firstfruits to God and to the Lamb' — they have not 'kept' what was given for distribution but have returned it fully.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'I have not eaten from it while in mourning, nor handled it while unclean, nor offered any of it to the dead' — the three ritual negations certify the tithe's purity: no contamination by death-mourning, ritual impurity, or mortuary cult. Christ is described as the high priest who is 'holy, blameless, pure, set apart from sinners, exalted above the heavens' (Heb 7:26) — the qualifications that no human priest fully met but that are required for the perfectly efficacious sacrifice. The tithe's ceremonial purity is a shadow of Christ's absolute moral and ritual purity, which alone makes his offering acceptable (Heb 9:14).</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Look down from your holy dwelling in heaven and bless your people Israel and the land you have given us' — the worshipper asks YHWH to look down from the heavenly sanctuary (contrast: the earthly temple is YHWH's earthly dwelling) and confirm the blessing. This prayer is answered definitively in Christ's session at the right hand of the Father: 'he always lives to intercede for them' (Heb 7:25). Jesus's high priestly prayer in John 17 is the NT counterpart to this blessing-petition: the Son who has ascended to the heavenly dwelling intercedes for his people on earth.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Today the LORD your God commands you to follow these statutes and ordinances. Keep them with all your heart and with all your soul' — the whole-heart and whole-soul obedience formula is the Shema's obedience dimension (Deut 6:5). Jesus identifies this as the first and greatest commandment (Matt 22:37-38) — not merely citing it but fulfilling it perfectly himself. Paul's contrast between letter and Spirit (2 Cor 3:6; Rom 7:6) is the distinction between external statute-keeping and the whole-heart response that only the Spirit regenerates in the believer (Ezek 36:26-27: 'I will give you a new heart ... and move you to follow my decrees').</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Today you have declared the LORD to be your God' (<em>ʾet-Yhwh heʾĕmartā hayyôm lihyôt lĕkā ĕlōhîm</em>) — the covenant formula of mutual self-giving. The worshipper commits to walk in YHWH's ways; YHWH in turn declares his commitment (v. 18). This is the covenant's mutual-declaration structure. In Christ, the ultimate covenant pledge is made: 'God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son' (John 3:16) — the divine self-giving that goes beyond declaration to incarnation and crucifixion. The believer's declaration 'Jesus is Lord' (Rom 10:9) is the covenant-declaration formula in its NT form.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'And the LORD has declared today that you are his treasured people (<em>ʿam sĕgullāh</em>)' — the divine counter-declaration of ownership and value. Peter applies this exact phrase to the church in 1 Peter 2:9: 'you are a chosen people, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, God's special possession (<em>laos eis peripoiēsin</em> in the LXX rendering of <em>ʿam sĕgullāh</em>).' Paul uses <em>peripoiēsis</em> (acquisition/possession) in Eph 1:14 ('who is a deposit guaranteeing our inheritance until the redemption of those who are God's possession'). The church's identity as treasured possession is grounded in the covenant formula of Deuteronomy 26.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'He will set you in praise, fame, and honor high above all the nations' — the covenant eschatology projects Israel's distinctive honor as YHWH's peculiar people into a universal visible reality. The NT applies this trajectory to Christ himself: 'God exalted him to the highest place and gave him the name that is above every name' (Phil 2:9). Those united to Christ share his honor: 'if we share in his sufferings, we will also share in his glory' (Rom 8:17). The holy people of vv. 18-19 is ultimately realized in the community gathered around Christ, 'a people holy to the LORD your God' (v. 19b), whose holiness derives from Christ's own.</p>",
  },
  "27": {
    "1": "<p>Moses and the elders give the charge together — the plurality of authorities delivering the commandment. The same communal delivery pattern appears in Acts 15:22-23 (the Jerusalem Council's letter sent by apostles and elders together), and ultimately in the commissioning of the church: Jesus's authority is expressed through the apostolic community he sends (Matt 28:18-20: 'all authority has been given to me ... therefore go'). The continuity of Moses's authority into the Promised Land through the covenant document anticipates Christ's words enduring past his physical presence: 'my words will never pass away' (Matt 24:35).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The large stones set up on the day of Jordan-crossing are a monument of covenant entry. Joshua 4's twelve memorial stones from the Jordan itself enact the same logic. Baptism in the NT is the Jordan-crossing moment — the passage from the old life to the new, marked by a public declarative act. Peter explicitly connects the flood/water-deliverance pattern to baptism (1 Pet 3:21: 'this water symbolizes baptism that now saves you'); the Jordan crossing is the same type pattern applied to Israel's covenant entry.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Writing the law on plastered stones was the ancient ANE treaty-inscription practice — Hittite suzerainty treaties were written on stone and deposited at the sanctuary. This law inscribed on stone is what Paul contrasts with the new-covenant inscription: '2 Corinthians 3:3: written not with ink but with the Spirit of the living God, not on tablets of stone but on tablets of human hearts.' The stone inscription is visible and external; the Spirit's inscription is internal and transformative. Jeremiah 31:33 announces the shift: 'I will put my law in their minds and write it on their hearts.'</p>",
    "4": "<p>The stones are set up specifically on Mount Ebal — the mountain of curse (v. 13), not Gerizim (the mountain of blessing). The law inscribed at the place of curse is a visual theology: the covenant document stands permanently at the location of covenant failure's consequence. Paul reads this in Galatians 3:10-13: the law pronounces a curse on all who fail to keep it, and all have failed. Christ 'redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us' — which Paul anchors in Deut 21:23. The Ebal stones bear the law; Christ bore the curse the law pronounces.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'There you shall build an altar to the LORD your God out of stones that no iron tool has touched' — the uncut stone altar preserves the altar's natural, creation character: no human craftsmanship mediates between the worshipper and YHWH. This ban on iron-tooled stones echoes Exod 20:25 and is the opposite of the idol-carving indicted throughout Deuteronomy (4:28: 'the work of human hands'). Christ as 'the stone the builders rejected' (Ps 118:22; Matt 21:42; Acts 4:11) is the divinely-appointed cornerstone that no human craftsman fashioned: 'the stone was cut out, but not by human hands' (Dan 2:45).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The burnt offerings on the Ebal altar are total-consecration offerings — entirely given to God, nothing retained by the worshipper. Christ's offering of himself is the ultimate burnt offering: 'he offered himself unblemished to God' (Heb 9:14), entirely given, nothing held back. The altar at the curse-mountain receiving burnt offerings anticipates the cross at Golgotha — the place of curse and shame that becomes the site of the most complete self-offering in history. The worshippers who bring their offerings will eat peace offerings here (v. 7) — but the burnt offering itself is wholly consumed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Peace offerings (<em>šĕlāmîm</em>) are shared meals: part to YHWH (the fat and blood), part to the priest, part to the offerer and family. The joy of eating in YHWH's presence on Mount Ebal — the curse mountain — is a remarkable image: the curse-location becomes the feast-location. The Lord's Supper participates in this dynamic: Jesus institutes the meal on the night of his betrayal, in the shadow of the cross — the feast is shared at the curse-location, and the eating is an act of covenant joy in the presence of the one who bore the curse (1 Cor 10:16: 'is not the cup a participation in the blood of Christ?').</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Write all the words of this law on the stones very clearly' (<em>bāʾēr hêṭēb</em>, inscribe with utmost clarity) — the law's clarity is not for decoration but for accountability: no one could claim ignorance. Paul's reflection on the law's clarity runs throughout Romans 1-3: the law makes the knowledge of sin precise ('through the law we become conscious of our sin,' Rom 3:20; 'I would not have known what sin was had it not been for the law,' Rom 7:7). The clarity of the stone inscription is the clarity that condemns; the Gospel's clarity (2 Cor 3:12-13) is the clarity that transforms.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Be silent, Israel, and listen — today you have become the people of the LORD your God' — the Levitical proclamation of covenant constitution at the moment of Jordan-crossing is the prototype declaration. Jesus's baptism (Matt 3:16-17) mirrors the structure: the Spirit descends, and the divine voice declares 'This is my Son, my beloved' — the covenant-constitution of the new covenant community in its Head. The silence commanded before the announcement reflects the gravity of the covenantal declaration; similarly, Jesus's transfiguration elicits the command 'Listen to him!' (Matt 17:5), the same posture of attentive silence before the divine address.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Obey the LORD your God by keeping his commandments and statutes' — the covenant obligation that flows from the new identity declared in v. 9. The sequence is grace-then-law (identity-then-obligation), not law-then-grace, which is why Paul argues in Galatians 3:17-18 that the promise to Abraham was not annulled by the law given 430 years later. Jesus's 'if you love me, keep my commands' (John 14:15) follows the same sequence: the love-relationship precedes and grounds the obedience, not vice versa.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The division of tribes for blessing and curse is programmatic: Moses sets up the ceremony before it occurs, and Joshua 8:30-35 records its fulfillment. The word-event structure — the command given before entry, fulfilled upon entry — reflects the prophetic pattern by which YHWH's word shapes history before it unfolds. Jesus's pre-announcement of his death and resurrection (Matt 16:21; Mark 8:31; Luke 9:22) is the same structure: the word precedes and interprets the event, so that when it occurs the disciples may believe (John 14:29: 'I have told you before it happens, so that when it does happen you will believe').</p>",
    "12": "<p>The six tribes on Gerizim for blessing — Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Joseph, and Benjamin — are all sons of the two full wives (Leah and Rachel), with the exception of Simeon. Judah is among the blessing tribes; the Messiah comes from Judah (Gen 49:10: 'the scepter will not depart from Judah'). The geographical staging of blessing from Mount Gerizim anticipates the beatitudes: Jesus pronounces covenant blessings on those who embody the covenant character (Matt 5:3-12), himself standing as the mediator of blessing rather than the one who merely recites it.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The six curse tribes on Ebal include Reuben (who forfeited the firstborn right, Gen 49:4), Gad, Asher, Zebulun, Dan, and Naphtali — the tribes of the concubines plus Reuben, Zebulun, and Gad. The curse-side staging does not permanently define these tribes' destiny; in Revelation 7:4-8 all twelve tribes are sealed, including those that stood at Ebal. Christ's work of redemption covers both sides: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us' (Gal 3:13) — there is no tribe beyond the reach of the atonement.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Levites call out the curses 'in a loud voice' (<em>qôl rām</em>) — the covenant sanctions are proclaimed publicly, unmistakably, to the entire gathered people. This public proclamation of the curse is the precedent for the NT's frank acknowledgment that all are under condemnation: 'there is no one righteous, not even one' (Rom 3:10-18). The loudness of the Levitical curse-proclamation is the equivalent of Paul's 'all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God' (Rom 3:23) — the diagnosis that creates the need for the cure. The Gospel's good news is unintelligible apart from this loud announcement of the bad news.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Cursed is the man who carves or casts an idol and sets it up in secret' — idol worship in secret is the act of divided loyalty: external covenant membership combined with private spiritual allegiance elsewhere. Jesus applies the idolatry-in-secret principle to the spiritual realm: 'no one can serve two masters' (Matt 6:24); 'your eye is the lamp of your body ... if your eyes are unhealthy, your whole body will be full of darkness' (Matt 6:22-23). The hiddenness of secret idolatry makes it the most corrupting form: it evades social accountability while corrupting the worshipper from within. Revelation condemns the 'Nicolaitans' and 'Jezebel' teaching for this same hidden compromise (Rev 2:14-15, 20-21).</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who treats his father or mother with contempt' — the honor-parents command (the fifth commandment, Deut 5:16) is here expressed in its negative covenant-curse form. Jesus sharpens this to include the internal attitude, not just external act: anger and contempt are equivalent to murder in the Sermon on the Mount's logic (Matt 5:21-22). More pointedly, Jesus condemns the Corban practice (Mark 7:9-13) in which scribal tradition allowed property-dedication to YHWH as an excuse to avoid supporting parents — a technical workaround that violated the spirit of the honor-commandment while satisfying its letter.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who moves his neighbor's boundary marker' — the property boundary as the sacred delimiter of each family's covenant portion in the land. Moving a boundary stone was a silent fraud that compounded over generations. The prophets condemn this specifically (Isa 5:8: 'woe to you who add house to house and field to field until there is room for no one else'; Mic 2:2). Jesus's parable of the prodigal son in reverse — the elder son who sees his father's estate as permanently fixed — and the warnings against accumulation (Luke 12:15-21) address the same acquisitive impulse that boundary-moving served. Christ embodies the opposite: he 'became poor so that you through his poverty might become rich' (2 Cor 8:9).</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who leads a blind person astray on the road' — the exploitation of physical disability is the particular test of community character. Leviticus 19:14 prohibits this alongside the prohibition of cursing the deaf. Jesus responds to the opposite imperative: he heals the blind rather than exploiting them (Matt 9:27-30; John 9). More broadly, he characterizes his mission as restoring sight to the blind (Luke 4:18, quoting Isa 61:1) — the Isaianic promise of the messianic age when the curse of disability exploitation will be reversed.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who denies justice to the foreigner, the fatherless, or the widow' — the covenant justice triad that appears throughout Deuteronomy (10:18; 14:29; 24:17-21; 26:12-13). The curse formulation makes the denial of justice to the vulnerable not merely unethical but covenantally destructive. James 1:27 defines true religion as 'looking after orphans and widows in their distress,' applying the Deuteronomic social obligation to the new covenant community. Jesus's judgment parable (Matt 25:31-46) bases the verdict on treatment of 'the least of these' — the hungry, thirsty, stranger, and naked — the NT equivalents of the foreigner-fatherless-widow triad.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who sleeps with his father's wife' — the violation of the father's sexual boundary, which is both an incest law and a property-and-honor violation (the father's wife was under his household authority). Paul directly addresses this in 1 Corinthians 5:1-2 when a Corinthian believer 'has his father's wife' — Paul demands covenant expulsion, applying the covenantal gravity of Deuteronomy 27:20 to the new covenant community. The specific phrasing 'violated his father's marriage' (<em>gicceh kĕnap ʾābîw</em>, uncovered his father's garment) is the cloak-coverage violation of Deut 23:1 — the same garment-image appears in Ruth 3:9 and Ezek 16:8 for the covenant-covering of marriage.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who has sexual relations with any animal' — the boundary between human and animal is covenantally ordered: image-bearers are not to violate the Creator's design-distinctions. While this specific prohibition requires little christological elaboration, the general principle of design-boundary respect is grounded in creation theology: 'in the beginning' God made them male and female (Gen 1:27; 2:24) — the Creator's design that Jesus himself cites as the authoritative grounding for marriage ethics (Matt 19:4-6). Sexual ethics in both testaments are anchored in the Creator's original design, not merely social convention.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who sleeps with his sister, whether she is his father's daughter or his mother's daughter' — half-siblings (same father, different mother) are included; this closes the loophole by which Abraham married his half-sister Sarah (Gen 20:12) under a different era's norms. The comprehensiveness of the incest prohibition reflects the covenant's ordering of the family as the foundational covenant unit. Paul's catalog of sexual immorality in 1 Corinthians 5-7 and his general principle 'flee sexual immorality' (1 Cor 6:18) are the NT expression of the same covenant-family-protection logic.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who sleeps with his mother-in-law' — the extension of incest prohibitions to the in-law relationships recognizes that marriage creates new family bonds that carry the same kinship obligations. Jesus's teaching on the indissolubility of marriage (Matt 19:6: 'what God has joined together, let no one separate') is the positive counterpart to the curse-prohibitions: the covenant bond creates genuine kinship that the community must protect, not merely the biological kinship. The marriage union is so profound that violations of its boundaries at the in-law level are covenant violations, not merely social impropriety.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who secretly attacks his neighbor' — the Levite's loud public curse specifically targets <em>secret</em> violence: the attack that evades communal witness and accountability. Jesus's warning about the 'darkness' of hidden deeds (John 3:20: 'everyone who does evil hates the light and will not come into the light for fear that their deeds will be exposed') addresses the same psychology of secret sin. The resurrection's judgment is the ultimate exposure of all hidden things: 'nothing is hidden that will not be disclosed, and nothing concealed that will not be known or brought out into the open' (Luke 8:17).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who accepts a bribe to kill an innocent person' — judicial corruption that weaponizes the court system against the innocent. The passion narrative fulfills this curse-scenario literally: Judas accepts thirty pieces of silver to deliver Jesus to the authorities (Matt 26:15; cf. Zech 11:12-13), and the Sanhedrin uses the legal apparatus to secure a death sentence against one they know to be innocent (Matt 26:59-60: 'they were looking for false evidence against Jesus ... but they did not find any'). The curse of bribed judicial murder falls on those who engineered the crucifixion; ironically, Christ's death under that unjust sentence is the means of atoning for the very sin the curse addresses.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Cursed is anyone who does not uphold the words of this law by carrying them out' — the closing, all-encompassing curse that makes the entire law a binary: either perfect compliance or the curse. Paul quotes this verse in Galatians 3:10 as the proof that all who rely on the law are under a curse: 'for it is written, Cursed is everyone who does not continue to do everything written in the Book of the Law.' Paul's argument proceeds: since no one can keep the law perfectly, all stand under this curse — therefore 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us' (Gal 3:13). This final Ebal curse is the most theologically decisive verse in the chapter: it is Paul's diagnosis that makes the Gospel's cure necessary.</p>",
  },
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'deuteronomy')
    merge_comm(existing, DEUT)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'deuteronomy', existing)
    il = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/interlinear/deuteronomy.json').read_text())
    out = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/commentary/mkt-christ/deuteronomy.json').read_text())
    all_ok = True
    for ch in range(26, 28):
        ck = str(ch)
        missing = [v for v in il.get(ck, {}) if v not in out.get(ck, {})]
        if missing:
            print(f'  ch {ch} MISSING: {missing}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'  ch {ch}: OK ({len(il.get(ck, {}))} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All verses present ✓')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
